Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, as measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community's statistics office located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the guiding interest rate by saying that falling interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it’s Catch 22 for the ECB: inflation “must be deterred” in order not to have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The futures market for cereals has increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the global price of oil rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1, this year, to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December, thus since 2002, it has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Polling) has never seen such low socialist support, i.e. 13 percent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
On loyal voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the economic situation of the country to be particularly serious has never been so high, it rises to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook for spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects an aggravation and only one tenth expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of the people surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, judged that the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of the respondents have confidence or much confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in political situation is the proportion of society that thinks that discontent with the Prime Minister can be treated without a change in government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of intention to vote, 60 percent of the respondents answered that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said that they would probably vote.
To make a comparison, for a "organize legislative election next Sunday", only 55 percent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to enrolment in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportion of those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by nearly twenty percent
Hypermarkets in the Budaörs commercial triangle have maintained the average price increase of 16 percent over the past year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economics)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase in value of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which “already flew off” in major grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nonetheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, that figure was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey, walnut and poppy nets have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s least expensive basket, we see a 12 percent difference while the difference between last year’s least expensive and this year’s most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices rose by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of <0xC2><0xA3>1,206, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has puzzled trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin appropriate to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the price increase of the Daily Cart has evolved so excessively that the most expensive cart was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest carts was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we saw a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some essential foods, the Statistical Institute noted a price increase of more than 30 percent over 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the latter's Daily Cart, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already quite expensive last year, increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, suppliers of flour occupy a stronger position than suppliers of eggs because they have managed to make accepting the sudden increase in prices also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets they visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-term storage foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumption items.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overload of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital, but shortly thereafter he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have been unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National System of Nosocomial Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Namely, it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of people carry the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without it developing a disease.
SA-caused infections (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a highly resistant bacterium that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicemia, on elderly, lightweight or having a weakened organism.
According to the director of the hospital János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily routine of hospitals.
Especially not to confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only there or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers are wearing rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however infection cannot always be prevented.
Sample sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favorable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is most common in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases only show up if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the doctor in charge of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, in other words, microbiological tests should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, wear gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by inhaled droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the sick should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the 22nd District Commissioner has been made.
It can be ruled out that the 22nd district commissioner, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death on Tuesday, would have driven drunk or stunned, Attila Morvai, a spokesman for the capital's public ministry, said on Friday after the statement was made.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd arrondissement police station crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself facing him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(Furthermore, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not an mitigating circumstance, according to the Road Code, a car that starts a corner must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to the police report, the accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is conducted by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
