The forces of the mega strike are coming together
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form, on Friday, their strike committee, which will be responsible for coordinating the indefinite strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as the railway traffic will be stopped almost completely and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1pm.
The League’s trade unions will announce on Friday afternoon the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers’ Councils.
The LIGA - MOSZ strike commission will also be formed, it will serve as the coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protesters will be held and, starting Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop working for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, starting from the day of the vote in parliament on the Health Funds Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not pass the Health Funds Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Funds Act will take place only late in the evening, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic jams are planned: the railways will stop working for an indefinite period and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different parts of the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike call, and the list of them is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report an indefinite strike, while others have declared a temporary work stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon, the M<0xC3><0x81>V (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Railways (VDSZSZ) were unable to find an agreement on minimum services, and as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 13h, Budapest airport between 7h and 9h of the morning, the Industrial Unions of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will strike at four hours, the Union of Teachers at 8 hours and the Union of Democracy at 2 hours.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternatingly, the Health and Social Workers' Union (EDDSZ) affiliated with the SZEF will strike a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new conception to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim seeks a guarantee in respect of retirement before the legal age, which would allow for the transfer into the system of the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Trade Union of Railways (VDSZSZ), affiliated to the League Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport regarding the secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August with the support of the Magyarországért Mozgalom Jobbik (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its “risk warning”, the company notes that, in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that “in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur as a result of the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary”.
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of the Hungarian political actors: “the public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Roma and the Hungarians.”
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the effect of increased attention from the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following increased publicity given to the reorganization of the radical and far-right Hungarian groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves "national self-defense association".
"The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their members for defense missions (disasters, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, in addition, evoking the incompetence of the police, the army, said another.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method which, based on the resentment of the society of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions in a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil character and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal traps of registering these associations in court, but they are also a political strategy.
