In Hungary, the law precisely defines the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as holidays.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also rest days, the latter all the more so that the awakeners can rest quietly.
In one year, we have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is the day of commemoration of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1 is the holiday of labor and on November 1 and 2, we remember the members of our family and friends who have died.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday preceding the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and all their employees, public servants and people working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions that operate uninterruptedly and in service, because of their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences, the majority of people rather make overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, therefore there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganised for the first time around the Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four consecutive days.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a day off on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the day of the new year falls on a Wednesday.
