Banks Want to Solve the Crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of England, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together the crisis of the financial markets.
More than a hundred billion dollars will thus be placed on the monetary markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the 9/11 attacks that individual central banks have decided to take concerted action to prevent, or even mitigate, the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," writes in its report to clients Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group.
"Central banks' concerted action has reduced the likelihood of a U.S. recession from 65 percent to about 50 percent," Baumohl said in a report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still expecting billions of more losses.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they must really grasp what can still follow," said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It sounds like the situation is really bad,” he adds.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The Central Banks made this choice after failing to bring down London's interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual borrowing, even though the U.S., Canadian and English central banks had repeatedly reduced their interest rates during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Tempus Consulting's Greg Salvaggio told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central bank’s approach will help to evoke the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem that is the fall of the U.S. real estate market.
