Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can come true if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or then a calm sea like a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
Now, there is only one island on which you will find much more and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
By the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the stronghold of their invasion of America.
Christophe Colomb described it as the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the deposit and transshipment place of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was erected at the very beginning of the 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who made it build, since everything that was a crime in the US (especially under the prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, buildings in height grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 1950s of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
In the bar of the National Hotel, a luxury hotel, we will mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the once imported jigulis and fiats have long since rotten, in such a salty and humid climate.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is substantially degraded, nowhere else in the surrounding area are there as splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings money if necessary, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varadero, on the coast of Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had returned from the plantations extended into the candy stores on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how small locomotives can be seen on the road, whose contemporary locomotives are only in museums elsewhere.
Where to direct his steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most famous places.
So there is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise, remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that those who love this writer should not miss the visit.
The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows on limestone soil.
Mogots, limestone balloons and rocks candlelight up from the bottom of the valley, and, with fertile soil grasping in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense plant carpet.
The valley is probably the place where the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You will be able to meet the final form of this product if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was shot.
Trinidad and Tobago
Ancient town founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the market, the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought it glory and wealth.
The wealth embodied in the beauty and the city-window character of this small city.
Colonial Spanish architecture, greatly influenced by later French settlers, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the mountainous Escambray, is a place so far apart that even in the 1950s there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stand aside.
We weren’t building anything, and that’s why we weren’t demolishing anything, everyone was just having a roof over their heads.
If you have, in Trinidad, more time than an afternoon, then it is also worth going to see interesting places in the surroundings, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the Candy Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música, which is animated after sunset and where the music is deaf only in the morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this village located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful of the island.
This view is certainly already influenced by the path that leads there.
The two roads that lead there from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and pass through a landscape almost unmarked by human activity.
UNESCO has included the East of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in fact, it was born about a hundred years after the trip of Columbus) and from the hill where the old castle-fort and the current hotel El Castillo, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountainous massif, the Bay of Pigs and the Island of Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of the former slaves could re a lot, about all this
But, as they say, it’s better to see it once.
In Afghanistan, the allies are passive, the Americans say.
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, affects the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the years to come.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should be, agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
Alongside the growing opposition from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and the coordination of the allies.
While the United States this week, through Defense Secretary Robert Gates, called NATO troops for more activity, Britain sees strengthening the Afghan government’s authority and intensifying development aid as a priority.
“Evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," Defence Secretary Des Browne told BBC.
Eighty-nine percent
Afghan insurgent activity is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense of the last five years.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 per cent compared to last year, up to 60 per cent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
Now, according to the United States, the Allies have reached their absolute limit in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
“We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we would need, and that’s not enough,” De Hoop told Reuters at the end of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo that lasted three days.
Who is Passive
In recent months, conflicts have also reigned among the countries involved in the issue of whether all allies are doing their best in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as rigorous as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate,” Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun called German soldiers lazy this week.
"Afghan fainties discovered: the Germans play, while ours fight," Sun wrote in a document supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild went back to counterattack by publishing a photo of a British troop during a rugby match in southern Afghanistan.
State debt will rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 crowns is borne by each Czech.
The total debt at the end of September was 842.7 billion crowns.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
Due to a better-than-expected change in state budget savings, the ministry reduced the projected amount to CZK 152.8 billion.
The debt of the State of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
During the nine months of this year, it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on government debt from early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 kronor is borne by each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has indebted more than 111 billion crowns.
"For now, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could exceed the limit of a trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns,” Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor’s forecast is similar: “We could exceed the trillion in 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget, which is not yet known.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene was changing, that policies were ready to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I don’t expect that change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the State is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated mainly by the accumulation of the deficits of the State budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bonds, rent securities, direct loans or, for example, by loans to the European Investment Bank.
Domestic government debt has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion kronor.
The foreign debt of the state has increased this year from 1.7 billion kronor to 123.3 billion kronor.
The so-called negotiable state debt reached 803.3 billion kronor at the end of September and as of June it decreased by 13.7 billion kronor.
The average debt receivability of the State was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third semester by 13 percent, which, given the current good health of the economy, is far too high.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by rent securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt increases, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be material to negotiate when pension reform comes," Pikora said.
Better Than Expected
This follows the 2007 government debt financing and management strategy, which the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected change in the state budget savings, the ministry reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the state budget, which is clearly going to reach 76 billion kronor this year, instead of the originally planned 91.3 billion kronor.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, i.e. 13.3 billion kroner, the 10 billion reserve for the payment of pensions, the financing of state annuity securities for 43 billion kroner and the repayment of the loans of the European Investment Bank in the amount of 1 billion kroner.8
She was appearing before a court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear.
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting pupils ages 6 to 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the Prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punishable by a whiplash.
This 54-year-old British teacher working at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with assaulting Islam and sedition under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asked her pupils, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” says school director Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Muhammad is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not carry any label with that name, but the problem is simply that of the prophet's representation considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never do anything that might be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said.
Opinion shared by many students of the teacher who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Recall that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the Prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This, of course, is a matter of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on Wednesday on the future status of the province, at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians completed a sixth and final session of talks Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Underlining that peace in the region was “at stake,” his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to honor their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
“There is no immediate anticipation of violence, but we are entering a very difficult period,” he said, adding that “obvious tensions exist.”
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The province’s 90 percent Albanian-speaking future could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, constituted the sixth and last session of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new UN mediation last August.
Americans and Europeans believe their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council's granting of independence to Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A declaration of unilateral independence? <0xE2><0x86><0x92>
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina says she is ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in her favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been found," Kosovo's president Fatmir Sejdiu said in the hotel in Baden, where the last-chance negotiations have been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, a former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, expressed his regrets.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations.”
"Domino effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still possible, warning the Kosovo Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
In particular, Belgrade says it fears a “domino effect” in a region still weakened by the 1990s wars of independence.
For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be returned exclusively to the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
"The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word"
"Only one solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.”
Fatmir Sedjiu told reporters that “the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the status,” adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanians would be made “in consultation” with Westerners.
Bush pulls out Israeli-Palestinian deal
President George W. Bush announced at the opening of the international peace conference he attended Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately enter into negotiations to find a definitive settlement of the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised he would do anything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, Palestinians must dismantle “terrorist infrastructure” and Israel must end its colonization activities, Bush said, recalling both sides to their obligations under the “roadmap” for peace they agreed to in 2003.
