A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archive documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only accessible for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or its beneficiaries.
The eleven States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States having been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will lead to research “including on the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced labour,” says Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as presumed homosexuality or the mental disability of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide proof of their detention, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
