Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus resembles Earth more than previously believed: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, similar to those that appear on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today provided evidence of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in the "Los Angeles" magazine.
According to the famous cyprin theory, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," explains Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
Today there should be hardly any living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the Earth's infernal twin, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of Venus Express in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venusian research, as no probe has been on its way to explore this planet since the 1980s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only emphasize the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the points in common with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more than initially assumed.
In addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, the researchers found a cloud whirlwind at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni from the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The so-called evening or morning star planet revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
