These aren't Warhols' boxes.
The one who connects the concepts of Sweden and boxes in wood, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on the list of Warhol’s works.
A large part of the eighty Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" thus questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today results in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the "Brillo-Boxes" at the Museum of Modern Art - of which the former director of the "Museum of Pontus Cadul" - has a
Ancient history is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not about works of art, but rather about their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as original Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes authorized, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum mistakenly claimed later that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have ceded to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, besides the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other private Swedish collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and punched, then applied with a pincer.
The texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a background layer on the laminate panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not make such a decision as the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in its class, the Moderna will cope with them in six different ways.
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
